to worship (particularly of Hindu gods), مرزا غالب (Mirzā Ġālib) , ‏چھوڑوں گا میں نہ اس بت کافر کا پوجناچھوڑے نہ خلق گو مجھے کافر کہے بغیر‎choṛūṅgā ma͠i na us but-e-kāfir kā pūjnāchoṛe na xalq go mujhe kāfar kahe baġairI will not leave off the worship of that idol of the kafirsthe people will not leave off without calling me "kafar"

(āīn) m (cआईन) #constitution: (āp) (cआप)#you (formal, polite and grammatically plural)Usage notesEdit#آپ is the most formal way of expressing "you" in Urdu and is used when addressing elders or those higher in social status. Because less formal forms could offend others, آپ is the safest way to express "you" unless there is reason to be less formal.#Because آپ is grammatically plural (adjectives and verbs etc affected by it take their plural forms) even when there is only one person being referred to, the term آپ لوگ‎ (literally: you people) can be used to specify that more than one person is being referred to because of T-V distinction.DeclensionEdit#declension of آپ#direct#آپ‎ (āp)#indirect#آپ‎ (āp)#ergative#آپ نے‎ (āpne)#genitive#آپ کا‎ (āpkā)#dative#آپ کو‎ (āpko)##See alsoEdit#تم‎ (tum) (mid level formality, grammatically plural)#تو‎ (tū) (complete lack of formality, grammatically singular)

(tum) (cतुम)#you, ye (mid level formality and grammatically plural)Usage notesEdit#تم is the mid level formal way of expressing "you" in Urdu and is used when addressing those of equal social status or those one has a close enough relationship with to justify the reduced formality. Because the less formal forms could offend others, آپ‎ is the safest way to express "you" unless there is reason to be less formal.#Because تم is grammatically plural (adjectives and verbs etc affected by it take their plural forms) even when there is only one person being referred to, the term تم لوگ‎ (literally: you people) can be used to specify that more than one person is being referred to.DeclensionEdit#declension of تم#direct#تم‎ (tum)#indirect#تم‎ (tum)#ergative#تم نے‎ (tumne)#genitive#تمہارا‎ (tumhārā)#dative#تمہیں‎ (tumhẽ), تم کو‎ (tumko)##See alsoEdit#آپ‎ (āp, highest formality, grammatically plural)#تو‎ (tū, complete lack of human formality, grammatically singular)

(tū) (cतू)#you, thou (informal, grammatically singular, possibly vulgar)Usage notesEdit#تو is least formal way of expressing "you" in Urdu and is used when addressing those of much lower social status or those one has a close enough relationship with to justify the reduced formality. Because the less formal forms could offend others, آپ is the safest way to express "you" unless there is reason to be less formal. The usage of تو varies. In some cases speakers would use it to refer to babies or children or even close friends, while others would use it only to refer to those they consider socially inferior, and some consider its use for people to be very rude in any situation. However تو, when used to address deities reflects a sense of reverence and closeness commensurate with the lack of formalities.DeclensionEdit#declension of تو#direct#تو‎ (tū)#indirect#تجھ‎ (tujh)#ergative#تو نے‎ (tūne)#genitive#تیرا‎ (terā)#dative#تجھے‎ (tujhe), تجھ کو‎ (tujhko)##See alsoEdit#آپ‎ (highest formality, grammatically plural)#تم‎ (mid level formality, grammatically plural)

column5: to#‏وہ روز اپنے پڑوسی سے لڑتا ہے۔‎‎vo roz apne paṛosī se laṛtā hai.He fights with his neighbor every day.#‏میں نے اپنی ماں سے پوچھا۔‎‎ma͠i ne apnī mā̃ se pūchā.I asked mother.#indicates a sense of removal or going: from#indicates exiting or separation#‏وہ گھر سے نکل کر ڈاک گھر چلا۔‎‎vo ghar se nikal kar ḍāk-ghar calā.He left from the house and went to the post office.#indicates source, cause, reason#‏یہ تلوار دو صدیوں پہلے لوہے سے بنایا گیا تھا۔‎‎ye talvār do sadiyõ pahle lohe se banāyā gayā thā.This sword was made from iron two centuries ago.#indicates origin, beginning#‏میں کراچی سے آیا ہوں۔‎‎ma͠i karācī se āyā hū̃.I've come here from Karachi.#‏کل سے‎ ― kal se ― since yesterday#comparative postposition: than#‏میں اُس سے ہوشیار ہوں۔‎‎ma͠i us se hośiyār hū̃.I'm smarter than him.#indicates passage of time#‏امی دیر سے یہاں بیٹھی ہوئی ہے۔‎‎ammī der se yahā̃ baiṭhī huī hai.Mom has been sitting here for a while.#indicates means or agency#‏اِس کپڑے کو پانی سے دھونا ہو گا۔‎‎is kapṛe ko pānī se dhonā ho gā.This cloth will have to be washed with water.#indicates manner of doing

The marker of the ergative case with perfective-aspect transitive verbs, ‏لڑکے نے کتاب خریدی۔‎‎laṛke ne kitāb xarīdī.The boy bought a book., ‏لڑکوں نے کتابیں خریدی۔‎‎laṛkõ ne kitābẽ xarīdī.The boys bought books.

(kā) Hindi spelling: का (kā) m#of#belonging to#‏عامل کی بیٹی‎ ― āmil kī beṭī ― Aamil's daughter#concerning#made of, consisting ofUsage notesEdit#کا‎ is a possessive particle in Urdu to show relationships with people and things, and in many cases it can be translated as an apostrophe s as possession would be used in English. It is not used to show possession by people of objects, the کے‎ پاس‎ construction is used for that. کا‎ is the postposition of the genitive case in Urdū and Hindī, and, as such, is also frequently used as an adjective termination, e.g. sone-kī ghaṛī, 'a gold watch'
column4: kāṭh-kā ghoṛā, 'a wooden horse'#The oblique form کے‎ (ke) forms a large number of compound pospositions such as کے‎ ساتھ‎ (with), کے‎ پیچھے‎ (behind), etc.InflectionEdit#Feminine: کی‎ (kī)#Oblique and plural: کے‎ (ke)

(āīn) m (cआईन) #constitution: (ko) Hindi spelling: को (ko)#marks the dative case: to#‏میرے بھائی کو پانی دیں۔‎‎ ― mere bhāī ko pānī dẽ. ― Please give some water to my elder brother.#‏لاہور کو‎ ― lāhaur ko ― to Lahore#‏اوپر کو‎ ― ūpar ko ― upwards#in, at the time of#‏میں شام کو گھر لوٹوں گا۔‎‎ ― ma͠i śām ko ghar lauṭū̃ gā. ― I will return home in the evening.Usage notesEdit#کو‎ (ko) marks the dative. It can be used as a postfix similar to -wards (e.g. اوپر کو (ūpar ko, “upwards”)
column4: آگے کو (āge ko, “afterwards”)).#It is suffixed to oblique forms of pronouns as well, e.g. the dative of میں‎ (ma͠i, “I”) is مجھ کو (mujh ko).#
